3.Display the percentage distribution of the data in each year using the pie chart.¶

In [6]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# assigning year variable
year_dist = df['year'].value_counts()

# creating pie chart
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))

#customizing plot
plt.pie(year_dist, labels=year_dist.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=20, shadow = True)
plt.title('Percentage Distribution by Year')
plt.show()

4.Plot and Understand the distribution of the variable "price per lb" using displot, and write your findings.¶

In [7]:
# create a customised dist plot

plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
sns.displot(data=df['priceperlb'], kde=True, bins=8, color = 'blue',common_norm = True)
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# add title
plt.title('Distribution of Price per lb')
plt.xlabel('Price per lb')
plt.ylabel('Density')

# display the plot
plt.show()

<Figure size 800x400 with 0 Axes>

Inference¶

  • From above plot we can see that average the price per pound falls this intervel 0.5 dollar to 1.3 dollar.
  • The number of data points with priceperlb values that are 175 or higher in the distribution plot.
  • In this plot average priceperlb as positively skewed, it indicates the presence of high values in the data.

5. Plot and understand the relationship between the variables 'numcol' and 'prodval' through scatterplot, and write your findings.¶

In [9]:
# data
X = df['numcol']
Y = df['prodvalue']

# plot the scatter plot
plt.scatter(X,Y)

# add the axes labels to the plot
plt.xlabel('numcol')
plt.ylabel('prodvalue')

#add title
plt.title('Scatter Plot')

# display the plot
plt.show()

Inference¶

  • There is a sitive linear relationship with number of honey producing colonies and value of production.
  • When one unit increasing number of honey producing colonies it tends to increase value of production.

6. Plot and understand the relationship between categorical variable 'year' and a numerical variable 'prodvalue' through boxplot, and write your findings.¶

In [10]:
sns.boxplot(data = df,x= 'year',y= 'prodvalue',width = 0.8, linewidth = 0.9)
plt.show()

Inference¶

  • The maximum production values is 7 dollars and minimum is 0 dollars.
  • The median of values of production is around approximately 0.3 dollars.
  • In this box plot evidently shows that significant number of outliers observed at the upper extreme of the scale.

7.Visualize and understand the relationship between the multiple pairs of variables throughout different years using pairplot and add your inferences. (use columns 'numcol', 'yield percol', 'total prod', 'prodvalue','year')¶

In [11]:
# creating a pair plot
num_column = ['numcol', 'yieldpercol', 'totalprod', 'prodvalue','year']
sns.pairplot(df[num_column], hue = 'year')
# show the plot
plt.show()

Inference¶

  • By pairplot we can comparing year with all other numerical columns.
  • Number of honey producing colonies has a strong positive linear relationship with total production value and value of production.
  • In comparison to other years, 2012 has a higher number of honey production.
